Chapter 1. The AAMA Project

Table of Contents

Project Overview
The Morphological Paradigm
Paradigm Formation and Manipulation
A Collaborative Archive

Project Overview

The Afroasiatic Morphological Archive is an on-going project with two goals:

  1. To assemble for exploration/investigation [through this tool?] a relatively comprehensive repertory of morphological paradigms -- in this case a large, but by no means complete, selection of Cushitic and Omotic verbal and pronominal paradigms, as they are documented in the best, most recent monographic treatments. To facilitate comparative exploration of paradigmatic material, in this initial release a small sample, gradually to be expanded, of other Afroasiatic is also included.

    It goes without saying that a set of paradigms does not constitute a morphology, but rather data for, or illustrations of, a language's morphology (in traditional grammars such a set usually constitutes an appendix or supplement to the actualy grammar) -- and there is actually a lively current debate about the theoretical status of such data-structures. However, the introduction to each language will contain a list of the morphosyntactic categories and values involved in the paradigms, with hopefully enough brief glosses and explanatory notes to give the interested by non-expert user an idea of what is going on [but always with the implicit injunction to consult the source monograph!]. An explanation of the organization and scope of the morphological data is contained in %-xref-% Part One of the documentation.

  2. To provide a tool for exploring and manipulating a database of morphological paradigms: specifically for the formation, transformation, combination, and comparison of morphological paradigmatic displays from a set of input morphological data, itself generally paradigmatic in form, with the goal of facilitating comparative insight into the interplay of morphological processes and morphosyntactic categories and values within and between between languages. An introduction to this aspect of the archive is contained in %-xref-% Part Two of the documentation

  3. To provide a framework for collaborative sharing of morphological material: In the first instance, Cushitic-Omotic and general Afroasiatic, but potentially also from other families as well. An introduction to this aspect of the archive is contained in %-xref-% Part Three of the documentation

The Morphological Paradigm

The working definition of morphological paradigm as used in the project: A large part of the morphology of a language (or, by extension, of a group of languages) is traditionally captured in paradigms -- tables of linguistic units whose shape varies systematically in accordance with different combinations of the values (e.g., singular/plural, first/second/third, masculine/feminine, past/present) of a set of properties (e.g., "number", "person", "gender", "tense"). In the default case, the units in question are words, and the paradigms show the set of possible forms which can be taken by an exemplary lexical item (here the "paradigm lexeme"). But paradigms can also be parts of words (affixes, clitics, vowel patterns, tone patterns), or words plus adjuncts (word+clitic, word+auxiliary ). Note that the criteria for assigning these latter compound constructions to morphology vs. syntax in the archive sources can vary significantly from one investigator to another, and that the notion of paradigm can also be used for data which is unambiguously semantic, syntactic, or phonological.

A set of paradigms for a single language is more or less complete to the extent that the information it contains is sufficient for learning, illustrating, or (analogically) inducing the inflectional morphology of the languge in question. Bi- or multi-lingual paradigms are used to illustrate systematic similarities and differences between related languages or varieties of languages, and are widely used as a tool in historical or typological investigations. Whatever the theoretical or psychological status of the paradigm (a range of contemporary views can be found in some recent collections such as Bachrach and Nevins 2008, and Blevins and Blevins 2009), the paradigm is indisputably an indispensible tool in the collection, organization, comparison, learning, and exposition of inflectional language data. Working with data of this kind unavoidably implies at some level working with paradigms

Paradigm Formation and Manipulation

[Rationale for formulating and manipulating mono- and pluri-lingual paradigms]

A Collaborative Archive

In addition, the archive is conceived of as an on-going and collaborative effort. We hope that eventually individuals/users with the relevant expertise will contribute new material from other areas of Afroasiatic and from Cushitic and Omotic languages, dialects, and varieties not covered here, and most importantly provide continuous correction and comment on data already contained in the archive (wiki-grammar). %-xref-% Part Three of the documentation contains the information relevant to the formatting and submission of extensions to the archive.

Chapter 2. Guide to AAMA Documentation

Table of Contents

General Information
Location-Speakers
Bibliographic Source
Paradigm Lexemes
Morphosyntactic Properties
Attested Archive Paradigms
Phonological Inventory

Note that at this point the documentation is in large part a lightly annotated set of lists progammatically generated from the output of a set of SPARQL queries, listing lexemes (output-. . . .rq[XREF]), morphosyntactic properties and values (output- . . . .rq[XREF], and a systematic index of paradigms (output-pdgmlabel-prop-val.rq [XREF]. Although we hope that this skeletal documentation will be helpful in finding and interpreting the data in the archive, it should be obvious what a distance there is between it and a morphological monograph or article. We trust that enough bibliography has been given to give the user a start on the more or less extensive literature that exists on each language.

Each language documentation will contain the following information:

General Information

Location-Speakers

The geographic location, estimated number of speakers, and attested varieties and subdialects of the language or language-variety in question. For the Cushitic-Omotic area, roughly the Horn of Africa and some adjacent areas in Sudan, Kenya, and Tanzania, a very helpful souce, and one usually linked to is the on-line Ethnologue catalogue, corrected or supplemented by other information, where necessary. The family-tree/genetic affliliation position assumed in the archive and presented in the systematic language index is not always identical with that of Ethnologue. Note that Ethnologue does not in principle offer coverage of ancient languages, and that other sources will be relied on and cited for those cases.

Bibliographic Source

Generally at this stage, the data from each language is taken from a single monographic source, whose reference is given in this section.

Paradigm Lexemes

Lemma and gloss of the lexical items which are used in the verbal paradigms.Where possible a single paradigm lexeme is used for each unique collection of morphosyntactic properties, including inflectional class. On occasion, the fragmentary nature of the documentation does not allow this. This is especially the case for dead languages, and for poorly or no longer attested varieties of living languages.

Morphosyntactic Properties

To be added: more detail about unevenness of coverage, reason for not choosing noun paradigms; rationale for what gets included; somewhat arbitrary boundary between phonological and morphophonemic/morphological alternation -- especially in area of inflection classes [what is considered a phonological alternation in one source is a inflection class in another]. Notion of base paradigm -- the paradigms which were actually entered into the data-base; these must always be available in txt or xml form [HAVE TO DECIDE WHICH ONE IS NORMATIVE!].

This section of each language's data documentation contains a list of the morphosyntactic properties and their values used in the paradigms of the language in question. These are given in separate sections for the major part-of-speech paradigm sets, the pronominal and the varbal. In addition, a separate section is given for Person-Number-Gender (PNG) properties, which occupy a unique overlapping position between pronoun (often as defining properties) and verb (as the principal subject-agreement properties throughout the macro-family). Note that in many cases this section contains only an unannotated list of the paradigm properties (= row/col headings), each with a list of its values. As documentation proceeds on a language-by-language basis, theexplanation of the morphological paradigm dimensions with become (asymptotically) more complete.

Where necessary a word of explanation or an illustrative gloss will be given for properties or values whose sense is not immediately clear; this is a work in progress, and the amount of explanation or glossing will differ from language to language and from one release to another. In this context however it cannot be overemphasized that a set of labeled paradigms is not the morphology of a language but a tool for the exploration of that morphology, and that the present archive is not a comparative grammar of Cushitic-Omotic (or Afroasiatic), but a presentation of an important part of the data that such a grammar (or set of grammars) must account for -- and as well an implicit invitation to collect and organize whatever additional material might be necessary to make such a grammar possible. The labels and explanatory glosses given in the documentation and paradigm notes will hopefully give the user an idea, perhaps more or less precise according to his or her background, of the morphosyntactic properties and values involved in the morphology of a given language. But they are no substitute for the fuller presentation which will be found in each case in the source monograph, book or article.

Property-value associations will differ in detail from language to language. But there is a great similarity in their inventory across the archive, and a typical documentation page will usually approximate the following outline, which contains some property-values associations and comments on them which apply virtually across the whole range of Cushitic-Omotic languages, and which will be linked to from individual language data documentations.

Cushitic-Omotic PNG Properties

  • PNG includes, almost universally in Cushitic Omotic, the following properties and values:

    • number

      1. singular sg

      2. plural pl

    • person

      1. first p1

      2. second p2

      3. thirs p3

    • gender

      1. masculine m

      2. feminine f

    It should be noted that not all combinations of number, person, and gender acutally occur, and in fact, with a few notable exceptions (e.g., Beja) the prevailing PNG pattern in Cushitic and Omotic is:

    number person gender
    sg p1 "⊤"
    sg p2 "⊤"
    sg p3 m
    sg p3 f
    pl p1 "⊤"
    pl p2 "⊤"
    pl p3 "⊤"

    I.e., where gender is distinguished only in the third-person singular. This pattern is so pervasive in Cushitic and Omotic that it will be referred to in the individual language documentation simply as the %-link linkend="cushOmPNG"-% Cushitic-Omotic PNG Pattern%-/link-%. PNG details will be given only when a language departs from this pattern. Note the symbol "⊤" ("down-tack", Unicode x22A4, logical "null:), which will be used in this archive for linguistic neutralization, in this case, of the gender distinction; i.e., sg-p1, sg-p2, and pl can be used in both masculine and feminine agreement contexts. For linguistic "null" the correlated symbol "⊥" (up-tack, Unicode x22A5) will be used.

Pronoun Properties

  • case: The pronominal (and nominal) case system in most Cushitic(-Omotic) languages is of the "marked nominative (or subject)" type, wherein the subject of a clause is marked with a special suffix, as opposed to an unmarked "base (or absolutive)", which serves as citation form, direct object, and form to which oblique case postpositions are suffixed. There is often some way of expressing a possessive/genitive case, either by suffix or final vowel lengthening. As with PNG, this case pattern will be referred in in individual language documentation simply as the %-link linkend="cushOmCase"-% Cushitic-Omotic Case Pattern%-/link-%.

    1. base ~ absolutive

    2. subject ~ nominative

    3. possessive ~ genitive

    4. oblique: when given, will be with a list of oblique case postpositions (usually NP-final

  • type: This will be a list of the pronoun types attested in the various paradigms

    1. independent

    2. possessiveSuffix

    3. demonstrative

    4. etc.

Verb Selector Properties: "Verb Selector" is a pre-verbal cliltic, or clitic chain which takes up, sometimes in a morphologically redundant fashion, sometimes not, a number of properties of the following verb. These properties differ from language to language, but often incllude pronominal subject markings, object parkings, and reference to verbal tense, aspect, and mood properties. The category, which is perhaps an areal one (cf. Bantu, from which the term derives), is limited (Oromo) or non-existent in more northerly Cushitic languages, fairly common in Omo-Tana, and highly developed in Southern Cushitic. Categories such as the following are common:

  • selProClass

    1. preVerbSel_SubjMarkers

    2. preVerbSelSubjMarkers

  • definite

    1. definite

    2. indefinite

  • mood

    1. indicative

    2. non-indicative

Verb Properties

  • polarity: For the most part "affirmative" vs. "negative", although some variations and elaborations occur. It should be noted that few Cushitic-Omotic languages have negative forms of the simple additive type, whereby a verb is rendered negative by simple placement of a negative word, clitic, or affix next to the affirmative form of the verb. Negative forms, although they usually involve some negative formative, frequently have a distinct morphology, frequently with fewer tam or PNG distinctions than the affirmative. These restrictions for an individual language will usually be summarized in "Verb Properties" section, with details, if necessary, either under the polarity or the tense property sections.

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • theme: The theme or derived stem sections usually involve the following categories, and in most languages, combinations of these are possible: causative+causative (double causative) is very frequent, as are middle+causative, passive+causative, and causative+passive. Grammars differ widely in the extent to which all possible combinations are documented, and in some languages there are distinct differences among dialects, varieties, and even idiolects as to the acceptability of various theme combinations

    1. base: Usually unmarked.

    2. causative: very frequently marked with prefix or suffix -s- (xref:: see below on prefixing and suffixing inflectional class)

    3. middle/benefactive: often with prefix or suffix dental, voiced, voiceless, or retroflex (xref:: see below on prefixing and suffixing inflectional class)

    4. passive: very frequently marked with prefix or suffix -m- (xref:: see below on prefixing and suffixing inflectional class)

  • composition: A subdistinction of %-link linkend="tam"-% Tense-Aspect-Mode%-/link-%

    • simple

    • compound

  • tam: Tense-Aspect-Mode.

    • simple: Most Cushitic-Omotic languages have simple (lexical verb only) inflectional paradigms corresponding to the following categories, sometimes with a complementary distribution between the jussive (with no second person) and the imperative (second person only).

      1. present

      2. past

      3. jussive

      4. imperative

    • compound: Many, and perhaps most, Cushitic-Omotic lanuages have compound (lexical verb plus one or more peripheral auxiliary or clitic elements), yielding a much more detailed inventory of tense, aspect, and modal distinctions. The treatment of these varies widely in the archive sources. Some investigators give them perfunctory treatment, or even ignore them completely. Others furnish long series of compound paradigms, to a point where it becomes difficult to see where Verb+Aux leaves off and regular Verb+Complement constructions start -- a notorious problem in any case in the debate over the boundary between morphology and syntax. In this archive we will simply reproduce the distinctions made in the source document. Since many of these distinctions are (morpho-)syntactically and semantically quite complex, in addition to the name, in the annotation I will simply give a translational paraphrase, and refer the user to the original source for more complete discussion. Typical compound paradigm categories are:

      1. perfect

      2. future

      3. progressive

      4. conditional

      5. etc.

  • inflectionClass: as in all languages, phonological and grammaticization processes conspire to create more or less marked morphophonemic differences in the verbal inflections of different sets of verbs.

    • affixationClass: Cross-cutting normal inflectional class in some branches of Cushitic (Beja and Omo-Tana, perhaps also Agaw) is an archaic Afroasiatic distinction between prefix conjugations (where the PNG subject markers are at least partially prefixed, and tam distinctions can be marked by internal vowel change) and suffix conjugations (where PNG subject markers are totally suffixed, and the verb base is invariant). It should be noted that , as opposed to Semitic, where this formal distinction corresponds to a tense-aspect distinction (past/non-past, perfective/imperfective) in all verbs, in the Cushitic languages which preserve it, this distinction is lexical, and a given verb-base is conjugated completely either in the prefix or the suffix pattern. Note further that in all Cushitic languages the productive pattern is the suffix-conjugation: only Beja and Saho-Afar have large numbers of prefix-conjugated verbs, and in the Omo-Tana languages the prefix-conjugated class is limited to a small inventory of at most a couple dozen high-frequency lexical items

      • prefixConjugation

        1. sub-class1

        2. sub-class2

        3. etc.

        4. etc.

      • suffixConjugation

        1. sub-class1

        2. sub-class2

        3. etc.

        4. etc.

  • special: almost every language has one or more infledctionally exceptional class of verbs, frequently involving the expression of "to be" in one or more of its senses and "to have"

  • nonFinite

    1. infinitive

General Information

Location-Speakers

Beja is a closely related group of language varieties and dialects spoken in the Red Sea coastal and hill regions in Sudan, Eritrea, and Egypt by more than a million individuals. The variety documented here is that of the Arteiga tribe in the vicinity of Port Sudan and Suakin, Sudan. This variety was studied by Richard Hudson (see especially Hudson 1976), and the data has been made conveniently available in a survey article by David Appleyard (Appleyard, 2007a).

Bibliographic Source

[HudsonR1976] The Beja Language. Richard Hudson. 139-154. Non-Semitic Languages of Ethiopia. Michigan State University Press. 1976. Lionel Bender.

[Appleyard2007a] The Beja Language. David Appleyard. 1. 447-480. Morphologies of Asian and Africa (2 vols). Alan Kaye. Eisenbrauns. Winona Lake IN. 2007.

beja-arteiga Paradigm Lexemes

The following lexical items are used in the verbal paradigms

lemma gloss properties
bs bury conjClass=prefix, pos=verb, rootClass=CVC
dbl collect conjClass=prefix, pos=verb, rootClass=CCC
dgy hear conjClass=prefix, pos=verb, rootClass=CCY
k-y be conjClass=suffix, conjType=irregular, pos=verb
lw burn pos=verb, rootClass=CVC
tam eat conjClass=suffix, pos=verb

Morphosyntactic Properties

Arteiga Beja paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

Morphological Type Of Paradigm entry

Some paradigms are categorized by the type of token in the paradigm:

  • tokenType

    1. affix

    2. compound

    3. stem

PNG Properties

  • Arteiga Beja makes more PNG distinctions than are found in the Cushitic-Omotic PNG Pattern

    Although Beja has the same property-value features as the rest of Cushitic (viz., sg/pl, p1/p2/p3, m/f), it has a more extensive (and more archaic) set of gender distinctions:

    number person gender
    sg p1 "⊤"
    sg p2 "m"
    sg p2 "f"
    sg p3 m
    sg p3 m
    sg p3 f
    pl p1 "⊤"
    pl p2 "m"
    pl p2 "f"
    pl p3 "m"
    pl p3 "f"

    I.e., where gender is distinguished not only in the third-person singular, but also in the third-person plural, and in the second-person singular and plural,.

Exceptionally some examples of noun plural classes, and of the postposition system which is shared by nouns and pronouns is documented here. Included in the pronominal paradigms are those of the definiteness marker.

    3. C

    2. equ

    1. defClass1

    2. defClass2

    3. defClass3

  • nearness

    2. near

Verb Properties

In the Beja verb generally, there is a complex interaction among the categories of polarity (with a marked affirmative-negative asymetry), conjugation class, root class, tense stem class, and tense-aspect-mode marking. The following tables to give a general orientation. For detail, the actual paradigms must be inspected and compared.

For all verb classes, tense-aspect-mode morphology is built on a system of seven stems. For the three root classes of the prefixing verb the stems are differentiated by affixation and internal vowel change; the suffixing conjugation stem remains invariable, but as can be seen from the paradigms themselves, comparable vowel alternations and affix series can be detected in the inflectional suffixes (which are commonly assumed to originate from encliticized stem-changing auxuliaries). Note that in the negative stem forms, even the suffixing conjugation verb receives prefixes. The following is a table of these stem forms (numerotation as in Hudson1976 and Appleyard2007; lexical items as above):

Table 4.1.  Beja tam Stem Classes

StemClass Label prefix-CCC prefix-CCY prefix-CVC suffix
1 pastStem -dbil- -dg- -lw- tam-
2 participleStem dibl- digy- lw- tam-
3 aoristStem -ii-dbil- -dig- -ii-lw- tam-
4 modalStem -ii-dbil- -dag- -ii-lw- tam-
5 presentStem -ee-dbil- -deg- -ee-lw- tam-
6 negStem -dabiil- -dag- -liw- -tam-
7 presentSgStem -danbiil- -dang- -nliiw- tam-


The distribution of these stems among the tense-aspect-mode categories is illustrated in the following table (where the stem-form is illustrated by the prefix-CCC root class verb dbl. Note that in the present affirmative tense, there is a stem distinction between singular persons (with infixed -n-) and plural (with prefixed -ee-).Note further that these are all non-compound tenses, with the exception of the negative past. The very limited and participle-based future tense has forms only for the first person singular and the second person.

Table 4.2. Arteiga Beja Tense Formation (ordered by tam category)

tam polarity StemClass StemClassLabel stem-form
present-sg aff 7 presentSgStem -danbiil-
present-pl aff 5 presentStem -ee-dbil-
present neg 1 pastStem -dbil-
past aff 1 pastStem -dbil-
past neg 2 participleStem dibl- (plus conjugated aux k_y 'to be')
aorist aff 3 aoristStem -ii-dbil-
future aff 2 participleStem dibl-
imperative aff 1 pastStem -dbil-
imperative neg 6 negStem -dabiil-
jussive aff 4 modalStem -ii-dbil-
optative aff 4 modalStem -ii-dbil-
optative neg 6 negStem -dabiil-
ptcpl-present aff 2 participleStem dibl-
ptcpl-present neg 6 negStem -dabiil-
ptcpl-past aff 2 participleStem dibl-
ptcpl-future aff 2 participleStem dibl-
ptcpl-conjunctive aff 2 participleStem dibl-
ptcpl-conjunctive neg 6 negStem -dabiil-

  • theme: The basic themes are

    1. B

    2. M

    3. R

    4. S

    5. S2

    6. SM

    7. T

    augment: each theme can occur in an augmented (intensive) or simple form. The only form agumentation documented here is vowel lengthening. However root and root-consonant reduplication is also possible.

    1. intensive

    2. simple

  • polarity

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • verbClass: some paradigms are marked for special classes of verb

    1. copula

    2. participle

  • conjClass

    1. prefix

    2. suffix

  • rootClass: the first three classes are of the prefixing verb, and correspond formally to Semitic strong, final-weak, and bi-consonantal roots. Verbs in the suffixing conjugation have a single, invariant root-class (although there are morphophonemic differences arising from stem structure which are not covered here).

    1. CCC

    2. CCY

    3. CVC

    4. invariable

  • tamStemClass

    1. aorClass

    2. modClass

    3. negClass

    4. partClass

    5. pastClass

    6. presClass

    7. presSgClass

  • tam: as noted in the above table, these are all non-compounding tenses (with the exceptio of the past negative, which is composed of a participle plus a conjugated form of the prefixing irregular verb k_y 'to be').

    1. present

    2. past

    3. aorist: What is here called the aorist is what Reinisch calls “plusquamperfect”,Roper “conditional”,and Hudson “past” (what he calls “preterite” I have here called past). Hudson’s glosses indicate a tense referring variously to a remote or anterior past event,a continuous or on-going past event,or a doubtful event,whilst in Roper the same form seems to be used mainly in the apodosis of unreal conditions. Almkvist’s informants were apparently unfamiliar with such a tense,though he notes that Munzinger had recorded a “plusquamperfekt”

    4. future

    5. imperative

    6. jussive

    7. optative

  • participle

    1. conjunctive

    2. future

    3. negative

    4. past

    5. present

General Information

General Information

Location-Speakers

Beja is a closely related group of language varieties and dialects spoken in the Red Sea coastal and hill regions in Sudan, Eritrea, and Egypt by more than a million individuals. The Atmaan variety is spoken in Eastern Sudan, and is described in Wedekind-etal2007.

Bibliographic Source

[Wedekind-etal2007] A learner's grammar of Beja (East Sudan). Köln: Rüdiger Köppe Verlag. 1928. Klaus Wedekind, Charlotte Wedekind, and Musa Abuzeinab.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

General Information

Location-Speakers

Beja is a closely related group of language varieties and dialects spoken in the Red Sea coastal and hill regions in Sudan, Eritrea, and Egypt by more than a million individuals. The Northern-most representative of Beja is documented here, that of the Bishari in Aswan and Sudan, studied by Herma Almkvist (1881) in one of the earliest monographs dedicated to a variety of Beja.

Bibliographic Source

[Almkvist1881] Die Bischari-Sprache Tu:-Bed'a:wiye in Nordost-Afrika (beschreibend und vergleichenddargestellet). Nova Acta Regiae Societatis Scientiarum Upsalensis. Serie Tertia 11.. Uppsala: Kaiserliche Akademie der Wissenschaften. 1881. Herman Almkvist.

Morphosyntactic Properties

Beja-Bishari paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

PNG Properties

  • Bishari, like the other varieties of Beja makes more PNG distinctions than are found in the Cushitic-Omotic PNG Pattern

    Although Beja has the same property-value features as the rest of Cushitic (viz., sg/pl, p1/p2/p3, m/f), it has a more extensive (and more archaic) set of gender distinctions:

    number person gender
    sg p1 "⊤"
    sg p2 "m"
    sg p2 "f"
    sg p3 m
    sg p3 m
    sg p3 f
    pl p1 "⊤"
    pl p2 "m"
    pl p2 "f"
    pl p3 "m"
    pl p3 "f"

    I.e., where gender is distinguished not only in the third-person singular, but also in the third-person plural, and in the second-person singular and plural,.

General Information

General Information

Location-Speakers

Beja is a closely related group of language varieties and dialects spoken in the Red Sea coastal and hill regions in Sudan, Eritrea, and Egypt by more than a million individuals. One of the Southern-most representative of Beja is documented here, that of the Beni-Amer in Barka, in what is now Eritrea, studied by Leo Reinisch (1893) in what is, along with Almkvist's study of the Bishari, one of the earliest monographs dedicated to a variety of Beja.

Bibliographic Source

[Reinisch1893] Die Bed'auye-Sprache in Nordost-Afrika. (I, II, III, IV). Sitzungsberichte der kaiserlichen Akademie der Wissenschaften in Wien.Philosophisch-historische Classe}, volume = {128/III, 128/VII, 130/VII, 131/III}. Wien: Kaiserliche Akademie der Wissenschaften. 1893. Leo Reinisch.

  • special

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

General Information

Location-Speakers

Beja is a closely related group of language varieties and dialects spoken in the Red Sea coastal and hill regions in Sudan, Eritrea, and Egypt by more than a million individuals. The variety of Hadendowa (Hadendiwa) represented here is that described by E.M. Roper (Roper1928) and spoken in Suakin, Sudan, where Roper was a colonial administrator.

Bibliographic Source

[Roper1928] Tu Bed'awie: An elementary handbook for the use of Sudan government officials. Hartford: Stephen Austin and Sons. 1928. E. M. Roper.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of Agaw (or Central) Cushitic language Kemant (Qimant) are spoken mainly in the Northwest Amhara region, north of Lake Tana. The number of actual speakers of Kemant is much smaller that the number of individuals who identify themselves as ethnically Kemant

Bibliographic Source

[Appleyard1975] “ A descriptive outline of Kemant”. David Appleyard. 316-350. Bulletin of the School of African and Asian Studies. 38. 2. 1975.

kemant Paradigm Lexemes

The following lexical items are used in the verbal paradigms

lemma gloss properties
fäy- go conjuctive=fay, pos=verb
iw- give conjuctive=conj4, pos=verb
was- hear conjuctive=was, pos=verb
xʷ- eat conjuctive=conj2, pos=verb

Morphosyntactic Properties

Kemant paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

PNG Properties

  • PNG

    Cushitic-Omotic Pattern.

Pronoun Properties

  • case: only marginally considered here. To be taken up in more detail when nominal morphology is added.

    1. base: frequently in -∅ or -a. NB, not the object case in Agaw!

    2. subject: unmarked or -i

    3. object: -s or -t

    4. possessive: -∅, -i, -äy, -də

    5. locative: -əl(i)

    6. dative: -əš, -äš, -z

    7. ablative: -z, -äz

    8. comitative: -(ə)di, -ädi

    9. allative: -əwä

  • proClass: covers a number of functions

    1. independent

  • proSet: In the independent pronoun setA is used in general for noun-phrase heads, setB typically for subordinates such as possessives. Both however can occur with case markers (Appleyard1975, p. 20).

    1. proSetA

    2. proSetB

    3. vAffSetA

    4. vAffSetB

Verb Properties

  • polarity

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • theme

    1. active: unmarked or -t- (sometimes denominative)

    2. causative: -š-

    3. passive -s-

    4. reciprocal: -sən-, -s-, reduplication+-s-

  • tam: Kemant has six main-clause tam values (imperfective, perfective, comound perfect, jussive, jussive2, and imperative), and seven subordinate-clause tam values. A number of the subordinate clause values are give formal rather than functional-semantic labels (a-, e-, n-subordinate), and are only partially glossed or described; all occur in affirmative and negative, except where noted. (Note that Appleyard's material did not allow complete documentation of all the subordinate-clause properties.)

    1. imperfective: "I hear . . ."

    2. perfective: "I heard . . ."

    3. perfectiveComp: compound perfect. "I have heard". Compound of a subordinate form of lexical verb, plusimperfective affirmative3 of wan- 'be'. Does not have negative distinct from perfective negative.

    4. jussive: 1p and 3p only

    5. jussive2: 3p only, no negative.

    6. imperative

    7. n-subordinate: various functions, including conditional

    8. gerundive: "he having heard . . ."

    9. relativeSubject: the antecedent is subject of its clause

    10. relativeOblique: the antecedent is not subject of its clause

    11. a-subordinate

    12. d-subordinate

    13. compSubordinate: compounding subordinate. Affirmative only

  • genHeadRel: the number property of the head noun in the relative oblique paradigm

    1. f

    2. m

  • numHeadRel: the gender property of the head noun in the relative oblique paradigm

    1. pl

    2. sg

  • verbClass

    1. finiteVerb

    2. copula

    3. dervStem

    4. interrogative

    5. subjMarker

  • finiteForm

    1. agentNoun

    2. infinitive

  • vSubjSet: In the verb the distribution of the two sets seems to be morphophonemically conditioned (Appleyard1975, p. 30).

    1. vSubjSetA

    2. vSubjSetB

  • pdgmType: a "meta-property" to distinguish some form displays which are not strictly speaking paradigms

    1. comparative

    2. exemplary

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following two tables give the feature-value combinations of the paradigms wich are actually documented in the archive. The first simply lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The second listing gives a spreadsheet-like row-by-column enumeration for the properties which are common to each paradigm; this eventually should be user-sortable to facilitate the comparative study of the paradigms. The second simply lists the common property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stands for: [gender:f,m,⊤; number:pl,sg; person:p1,p2,p3] -- i.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of theAgaw (or Central) Cushitic language: Bilin is spoken mainly in the vicinity of the town Keren. The variety represented here is that described in Appleyard2007b.

Bibliographic Source

[Appleyard2007b] Bilin Morphology. David Appleyard. 1. 481-504. Morphologies of Asian and Africa (2 vols). Alan Kaye. Eisenbrauns. Winona Lake IN. 2007.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of Agaw (or Central) Cushitic language Khamtanga is spoken in the North Amhara region, by the Chamir people. Variety described by Appleyard 1987ab

Bibliographic Source

[Appleyard1987a] “ A grammatical sketch of Khamtanga I”. David Appleyard. 241-266. Bulletin of the School of African and Asian Studies. 50. 1987.

[Appleyard1987b] “ A grammatical sketch of Khamtanga II”. David Appleyard. 470-5-7. Bulletin of the School of African and Asian Studies. 50. 1987.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of Agaw (or Central) Cushitic language: Awngi is spoken mainly in the Amhara region, southwest of Lake Tana, and in scattered nearby localities. The variety represented here is that of the village of Bert'a Abbo in the province of Agawmeder, as described by Robert Hetzron in his 1969 monograph.

Bibliographic Source

[Hetzron1969b ] The Verbal System of Southern Agaw. Near Easter Studies, vol. 12. LosAngeles: University of California Press. 1969. Robert Hetzron.

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of Afar are spoken by more than a million individuals in Ethiopia, Djibouti, and Eritrea. It is very closely related to Saho

Bibliographic Source

[Parker-Hayward1985 ] Appendix A: A Concise Outline of Phonology and Morphology . Richard J. Hayward . 214-297. An Afar-English-French Dictionary. School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London. London . 1985. Richard J. Hayward and E. M. Parker.

Paradigm Lexemes

The following lexical items are used in the verbal paradigms:

lemma gloss properties
ab- do conjClass=suffix, pos=verb
anày-ʕunɗa- be softly spoken conjClass=compoundStative, pos=verb
eeɗeg- know conjClass=prefix, pos=verb
fak- open conjClass=suffix, pos=verb
kàɗ-hee bow conjClass=compoundTransitive, pos=verb
le- have conjClass=stativeIrreg, pos=verb
meʕ- be good conjClass=stative, pos=verb
ruffa-eɗḥ- become happy conjClass=compoundIntransitive, pos=verb
uduur- return conjClass=prefix, pos=verb

Morphosyntactic Properties

Afar paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

PNG Properties

  • PNG

    Afar follows the Cushitic-Omotic PNG Pattern.

Pronoun Properties

  • case: Afar follows the Cushitic-Omotic Pattern. In addition there is a reflexive pronoun and an emphatic foregrounding pronoun. Both the possessive and the emphatic occur with what Hayward 1985 terms "m-nominalizations" (p. 236) which can frequently be glossed "the ones/things pertaining-to/belonging-to".

    1. absolutive

    2. nominative

    3. possessive

    4. possessive-m

    5. emphatic

    6. emphatic-m

    7. reflexive

  • proClass

    1. nonReflexive

    2. reflexive

  • pdgmSubType

    1. independent

    2. possessiveDefinite

Verb Properties

  • conjClass: In addition to the old Afroasiatic distinction between regular prefixing and suffixing conjugation class verbs, as found in Beja and in the Omo-Tana languages, within the suffixing verbs, Afar distinguishes a distinct stative subclass.There are in addition three suffixing classes of compound verbs consisting of an invariant first element: and a specially conjugated second verb element. Finally, there is the characteristic small inventory of "special" verbs.

    1. prefix: paradigm lexeme '-uduur-' "return"

    2. suffix: paradigm lexeme 'fak-' "open"

    3. stative: paradigm lexeme 'meʕ-' "be good"

    4. compoundStative: Invariant+ʕunɗ- ; paradigm lexeme anày-ʕunɗ- "be soft-spoken"

    5. compoundIntransitive: Invariant+eɗḥ- "say' ;paradigm lexeme ruffa-eɗḥ- "be happy"

    6. compoundTransitive: Invariant+hee- "put"; paradigm lexeme kàɗ-hee "bow"

    7. special

      • Copula: kinni

      • Locative-existential: en (frequent as auxiliary)

      • Possessive: le- (also used to form the future)

      • Negative: sinni 'be without'

  • polarity

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • theme: The semantic, lexical, and formal variety of what Hayward 1985 (pp. 243-252) calls "extended stem (ES)" verbs is, as Hayward says (p. 245), with some understatement, "very considerable." The usual major categories occur, with many combinations, permutations, and variants, and has not lent itself to simple paradigmatic treatment. See the extensive "Table 16" with notes in Hayward 1985 (pp. 245-251).

    1. base

    2. causative

    3. middle

    4. passive

  • tam: tense-aspect-mood properties

    General Characteristics: Afar, in the detailed analysis of Hayward 1985, displays a complex interaction between simple and compound, affirmative and negative tense-aspect properties and values.The following table (a slight adaptation of the paradigm afar-VTAMStemStructure) gives the main verb stem structure and the structure of the auxiliaries and/or adjuncts, affirmative and negative, for each of the 26 tam forms recognized by Hayward. Note that what Hayward calls the perfect/imperfect participle is simply the perfect/imperfect form of the verb with a suffix -h, which in many cases may be roughly paraphrased as "(NP) having V-ed"; the same suffix -h can occur optionally with the main verb in clauses in which the verbal-predicate, as opposed to a nominal constituent, is being foregrounded. Among the main verb adjuncts are a number of invariant words/clitics; and the conjugated auxiliaries: the prefixing verb -en- 'be', and the suffixing sug- 'stay, wait', wa- ' ', and ɗaaɗ - ' ' , In the absence of a detailed analysis, an approximate gloss (that of Hayward, in fact) is given for the affirmative forms. As example of each polarity-tam comination we give the 3msg form of the suffixing verb fak- 'open'.:

    pol tam-label mainVerbForm auxAdjunctForm gloss example
    aff perfect perfect (-h)[invar] he opened / has opened fak-e(-h)
    aff imperfect imperfect (-h)[invar] he opens / is opening / will open fak-a(-h)
    aff perfectPast1 perfectParticiple en[perf] he had opened fak-è-h y-en
    aff perfectPast2 perfectParticiple sug[perf] he had opened fak-è-h sug-e
    aff perfectPresent perfectParticiple en[imperf] he has opened fak-è-h y-an
    aff imperfectPast1 participle-k[invar] en[perf] he was /had been opening / used to open fàkak y-en
    aff imperfectPast2 participle-k[invar] sug[perf] he was /had been opening / used to open fàkak y-an
    aff imperfectPresent imperfectParticiple en[imperf] he is opening fak-à-h y-an
    aff anticipatory eForm[invar] -le [enclitic verb 'have'] he will open fakè-le
    aff perfectAnticipatory perfectParticiple sug[anticipatory] he will have opened fak-è-h sug-è-le
    aff imperfectAnticipatory participle-k[invar] sug[anticipatory] he will be opening fàk-ak sug-è-le
    aff jussive jussive ⊤ let him open fàk-ay
    aff requestive[p1 only] requestive ⊤ may I open? fak-o
    aff intentive u-Form wa- he is intending / about to open fàk-u wa-a
    aff imperfectProbable1 u-Form takkeh[invar] he may open fàk-u takkeh
    aff imperfectProbable2 imperfect-m takkeh[invar] he may open fak-à-m takkeh
    aff perfectProbable perfect-m takkeh[invar] he may / might have opened fak-è-m takkeh
    aff imperative[p2 only] imperative ⊤ open! fàk
    aff conditional1 perfect k[invar] if he opens fak-e-k
    aff conditional2 perfect pro[absolutive] tekkek[invar] if he opens fak-è kaa tekkek
    aff perfectConditional perfectParticiple sug[perf]-k[invar] if he has opened fak-è-h sug-e-k
    aff contrafactual stem -inn-[subordinate]-y if he had opened / had he opened fak-inn-a-y
    aff purposive1 u-Form -h[invar] that he open fàk-u-h
    aff purposive2 imperfect -nkeh[invar] that he open fak-à-nkeh
    aff hypothetical eForm[invar] ɗaaɗ [perf] he would have opened fakè ɗaaɗ-e
    neg perfect mà-stem -inn-[subordinate] mà-fak-inn-a
    neg imperfect mà-imperfect ⊤ mà-fak-a
    neg perfectPast1 perfectParticiple mà-en-(i)nn-[subordinate] fak-è-h mà-na-nn-a
    neg perfectPast2 perfectParticiple mà-sug-inn-[subordinate] fak-è-h mà-sug-inn-a
    neg perfectPresent perfectParticiple mà-en[imperf] fak-è-h mà-y-an
    neg imperfectPast1 participle-k[invar] mà-en-(i)nn-[subordinate] fàkak mà-na-nn-a
    neg imperfectPast2 participle-k[invar] mà-sug-inn-[subordinate] fàkak mà-sug-inn-a
    neg imperfectPresent imperfectParticiple mà-en[imperf] fak-à-h mà-y-an
    neg anticipatory (= neg imperfect) mà-imperfect ⊤ mà-fak-a
    neg perfectAnticipatory perfectParticiple mà-sug[imperf] fak-è-h mà-sug-a
    neg imperfectAnticipatory participle-k[invar] mà-sug[imperf] fàkak mà-sug-a
    neg jussive eForm[invar] wa[jussive] fakè wà-ay
    neg requestive[p1 only] ma-requestive ⊤ ma-fako
    neg intentive u-Form mà-wa[imperf] fàk-u mà-wa-a
    neg imperfectProbable1 eForm[invar] wa[u-Form] takkeh[invar] fakè wày-u(-h) takkeh
    neg imperfectProbable2 eForm[invar] wa[imperf]–m takkeh[invar] fakè wa-a-m takkeh
    neg perfectProbable perfect-m wa[perf]–m takkeh[invar] fakè we-e-m takkeh
    neg imperative mà-stem-in[imperative] ⊤ mà-fak-in
    neg conditional1 eForm[invar] wa[perf]-k fakè we-e-k
    neg conditional2 eForm[invar] wa[imperf] pro[absolutive] tekkek fakè wa-a kaa tekkek
    neg perfectConditional perfectParticiple sug[eForm] wa[perf]-k fak-è-h sugè we-e-k
    neg contrafactual eForm[invar] wa-inn-[subordinate]-y fakè wa-nn-a-y
    neg purposive1 eForm[invar] wa[uForm]-h fakè wày-u-h
    neg purposive2 eForm[invar] wa[imperf]-nkeh fak-è wa-à-nkeh
    neg hypothetical eForm[invar] mà-ɗaaɗ [perf] fakè mà- ɗaaɗ-e

    • simple: As can be seen from the table, in the affirmative only the imperative/jussive/requestive can be said to be truly non-compound, and the perfect/imperfect marginally so, in that a -h adjunct can be dropped if the verb is not the foregrounded element in a clause. In the negative, only the imperfect and the requestive/imperative occur without adjuncts.

      1. perfect

      2. imperfect

      3. jussive

      4. requestive

      5. imperative

    • compound: consult the above table.

      2. perfectPast2

      3. perfectPresent

      4. imperfectPast1

      5. imperfectPast2

      9. imperfectAnticipatory

      17. conditional2

    • stative

      1. pastState1

      2. pastState2

      3. presentState1

      4. presentState2

      5. contrafactualStative

    • non-finite

      1. VH-Participle

      2. i-Form

      3. infinitive

      4. relativeIndeterminate

  • special

  • verbClass

    1. nonFinite

    2. stemForm

    3. subjMarker

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following two tables give the feature-value combinations of the paradigms wich are actually documented in the archive. The first simply lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The second listing gives a spreadsheet-like row-by-column enumeration for the properties which are common to each paradigm; this eventually should be user-sortable to facilitate the comparative study of the paradigms. The second simply lists the common property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of Saho are spoken in Eritrea and Ethiopia (Irob dialect only). The language is very closely related to Afar .

Bibliographic Source

[Welmers1952] “Notes on the structure of Saho 1, 2 ”. W. E. Welmers. 145-162; 236-251. Word. 8. . 1952.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of Oromo are spoken by millions of individuals over much of central and southern Ethiopia . The variety treated here is characteristic of the west-central region, specifically Wallagga. Other more-or-less distinct varieties are the Eastern , Borana-Arsi-Guji, and Orma (spoken in Kenya).

Bibliographic Source

[Gragg76] Oromo of Wallagga. Gene Gragg. 166-195. Non-Semitic Languages of Ethiopia. Michigan State University Press. 1976. Lionel Bender.

Morphosyntactic Properties

Oromo paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

PNG Properties

  • Oromo follows the Cushitic-Omotic PNG Pattern

Pronoun Properties

  • case

    1. base

    2. possessive

    3. subject

  • type

    1. independent

    2. possessiveSuffix

Verb Properties

General Characterization: In the affirmative main clause, Oromo makes the usual simple tense distinctions. The non-compound categories present/past, affirmative/negative, and main/subordinate interact in the following complex way, illustrated in the table below. In the present affirmative, the main clause PNG suffixes have a characteristic -a vocalization as opposed to a -u vocalization in the subordinate. In the present negative, the mainClause forms have the same -u PNG series as the subordinate main; the present negative subordinate has an invariant -ne PNG suffix. In the past tense, there is no distinction between main and subordinate forms. The affirmative past tense has an -e PNG vocalization, while the negative main and subordinate now has the invariant -ne.The following table illustrates the distribution of PNG+tense markers, where the PNG sequence is: 1sg, 2sg, 3msg, 3fsg, 1pl, 2pl, 3pl (i.e., the Cushitic-Omotic Pattern):

Tense Affirmative Negative
Main Subordinate Main Subordinate
Present -a -u -u -ne
-ta -tu -tu
-a -u -u
-ti -tu -tu
-na -nu -nu
-tu -tani/u -tani/u
-u -ani/u -ani/u
Past -e -ne
-te
-e
-te
-ne
-tan(i)
-an(i)

In the compound tenses Oromo makes characteristic distinctions of tense and aspect (perfectivity and progressivity) as described in documentation guide, and indicated here, as usual. by approximate glosses.

  • polarity

    1. affirmative: if "emphatic" or foregrounded, can be preceeded by proclitic (h)ín- in present tense.

    2. negative: takes negative proclitic ((h)i)n-, plus special negative tenses, as described above. When reduced to simple segment -n-, the particle can be encliticized to preceeding word.

  • theme

    1. base

    2. causative

    3. middle

    4. passive

  • tam

    • simple

      1. present

      2. past

      3. jussive

      4. imperative

    • compound

      1. perfect. Structure:V[past]+jir-[pres] Gloss:"he has gone, . . ."

      2. pluperfect. Structure:V[past]+tur-[pst] Gloss: "he had gone, . . ."

      3. presentProgressive. Structure:V[participle]+jir-[pres] Gloss: "he is going, . . ."

      4. pastProgressive. Structure:V[participle]+tur-[past] Gloss: "he was going, . . ."

      5. pluperfectProgressive. Structure:V[participle]+jir-[pres]+tur-[past] Gloss: "he had been going, . . ."

      6. futureDefinite. Structure:V[infiitive]+f+jir-[pres] Gloss: "he will go, . . ."

      7. futureIndefinite. Structure:hín+V[pres]+ta'a[3msg-invariable] Gloss: "he may go, . . ."

      8. futurePerfect. Structure:V[infinitive]+f+tur-[past] Gloss: "he will have gone, . . ."

      9. conditional. Structure:hín+V[pres]+tur-[past] Gloss: "if he goes, . . ."

  • special

    • BE: Oromo has an uninflected enclitic for the simple positive (-ɗa) and negative (-miti) copula. Otherwise for BE it uses suppletively the following verbs:

      1. tur-: predication past-tense; existence, past

      2. ta-: predication, non-past/non-present; occurrence, all tenses

      3. jir-: existence, present

  • nonFinite

    1. infinitive

    2. agent

    3. gerund

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following two tables give the feature-value combinations of the paradigms wich are actually documented in the archive. The first simply lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The second listing gives a spreadsheet-like row-by-column enumeration for the properties which are common to each paradigm; this eventually should be user-sortable to facilitate the comparative study of the paradigms. The second simply lists the common property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

Chapter 16.  Standard Somali Language Data

General Information

Location-Speakers: Standard Somali

Standard Somali is based principally on the Northern variety of a group of closely related " Somaloid" language varieties spoken in the Horn of African and Kenya. Standard Somali is spoken throughout the region historically known as Somalia, and in adjacent countries (Djibouti, Ethiopia, Kenya). The paradigms are a combination of Saeed1999 and Orwin1995.

Bibliographic Source: Standard Somali

[Saeed1999] Somali. London Oriental and African Language Library. vol. 10 . Amsterdam/Philadelphia: J. Benjamins . 1999. John Ibraim Saeed.

[Orwin1995] Colloquial Somali. Colloquial Series. London/New York: Routledge. 1995 . Martin Orwin.

Paradigm Lexemes: Standard Somali

The following lexical items are used in the verbal paradigms:

Table 16.1. The following lexical items are used in Standard Somali verbal paradigms:

Lemma Gloss LexProperties Note
yimi come conjClass:prefix
súg wait for conjClass:suffix, subConj:C1
kári cook conjClass:suffix, conjSubClass:C2A,
yarèe make small (cf. yár ‘small’) conjClass:suffix, conjSubClass:C2B,
kéen give conjClass:suffix, conjSubClass:C1,
yiɗi say conjClass:prefix
joogsó stop oneself conjClass:suffix, conjSubClass:C3A,
yiqiin know conjClass:prefix
yahay be conjClass:prefix,
yiil be (in a place) conjClass:prefix
qaadó take for oneself conjClass:suffix, subConj:C3B


Standard Somali Morphosyntactic Properties

Standard Somali paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

PNG Properties

  • PNG

    Standard Somali follows the Cushitic-Omotic PNG Pattern.

Pronoun Properties: Standard Somali

  • case

    1. nominative [1]

    2. object [2]

  • genPoss

    1. f [3]

    2. m [4]

  • morphSubClass

    1. subClass1 [5]

    2. subClass2 [6]

  • proClass

    1. independent [7]

    2. objClitic [8]

    3. possessive [9]

    4. subjClit [10]

Standard Somali Verb Properties

  • polarity

    1. affirmative [11]

    2. negative [12]

    3. negative2 [13]

  • theme: no paradigmatic information on this property in archive

  • TAM

    1. conditional [14]

    2. future [15]

    3. imperative [16]

    4. optative [17]

    5. pastGeneral [18]

    6. pastHabitual [19]

    7. pastIndependent [20]

    8. pastProgressive [21]

    9. potential [22]

    10. presentGeneral [23]

    11. presentProgressive [24]

    12. presentProgressive2 [25]

  • pdgmType

    1. compound [26]

    2. structure [27]

  • verbClass

    1. infinitive [28]

    2. pastInvar [29]

  • inflectionClass: as in all languages, phonological and grammaticization processes conspire to create more or less marked morphophonemic differences in the verbal inflections of different sets of verbs.

    • conjClass

      1. prefix [30]

      2. suffix [31]

    • conjSubClass

      1. C1 [32]

      2. C2A [33]

      3. C2B [34]

      4. C3A [35]

      5. C3B [36]

  • special

    • clauseCase

      1. absolutive [37]

      2. subject [38]

    • clauseType

      1. [39]

      2. full [40]

      3. fullReducedVariant [41]

      4. main [42]

      5. reduced [43]

      6. subordinate [44]

      7. subordinateVariant [45]

    • npg

      1. variable [46]

      2. invariable [47]

Attested Archive Paradigms: Standard Somali

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for: gender:f,m,⊤ number:pl,sg person:p1,p2,p3 I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of Rendille are spoken in Kenya, between Lake Turkana and Mt. Marsabit.

Bibliographic Source

[Pillinger-Galboran1999] A Rendille dictionary: Including a grammatical outline and an English-Rendille Index. Cushitic Language Studies, vol. 14 . Köln: Köppe Verlag. 1999. Steve Pillinger and Letiwa Galboran.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Representing the northern branch of the Omo-Tana language sub-family, Bayso is spoken in villages in the vicinity of, and islands in Lake Abaya.

Bibliographic Source

[Hayward1978] “Bayso revisited. Some preliminary linguistic observations, Part I”. Richard Hayward. 539–570. Bulletin of the School of African and Asian Studies. 41. 4. 1978.

[Hayward1979] “Bayso revisited. Some preliminary linguistic observations, Part II”. Richard Hayward. 101–132. Bulletin of the School of African and Asian Studies. 42. 1. 1979.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Jara is a variety of CentralBoni spoken for the most part by residents of the town of Mangai in North-eastern Kenya. It was the object of a dialect study by Bernd Heine published in 1982.

Bibliographic Source

[Heine1982] Boni Dialects. Language and dialect atlas of Kenya, vol. 10. Berlin: Dietrich Reimer Verlag. 1982. Bernd Heine.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Kilii is a variety of NorthernBoni. The material archived here is from a dialect study by Bernd Heine published in 1982, and is based the speech of one person, who spent most of his life in the town of Badada in South-eastern Somalia.

Bibliographic Source

[Heine1982] Boni Dialects. Language and dialect atlas of Kenya, vol. 10. Berlin: Dietrich Reimer Verlag. 1982. Bernd Heine.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

Varieties and subdialects of the Western Omo-Tana language Arbore are spoken near Lake Stefanie.

Bibliographic Source

[Hayward1984a] The Arbore Language: A First Investigation Including a Vocabulary. Richard J. Hayward. . Helmut Buske Verlag. Hamburn. 1984. Kuschitische Sprachstudien 2.

arbore Paradigm Lexemes

The following lexical items are used in the verbal paradigms

Lemma Gloss Properties
beeḳoW- become wounded dervStem=inchoative, pos=verb
hariyAƊ- feel (tr.) dervStem=middle1, pos=verb
kumAHAƊ- bow dervStem=middle3, pos=verb
raf- sleep conjClass=suffix, dervStem=base, pos=verb, subConj=nonContracting
rakkAƊƊ- experience trouble dervStem=middle4, pos=verb
waññoHAƊ- become old dervStem=middle2, pos=verb
zer(e)n- pierce conjClass=suffix, pos=verb, subConj=contracting
ñoorIS- cause to arrive dervStem=causative1, pos=verb
ʔEEčč- come conjClass=prefix, patternClass=pattern2, pos=verb
ʔElɗ- ~ ʔEll- ~ ḳeʔ-(suff) stand patternClass=pattern2, pos=verb
ʔEḳEs- ~ ʔigis- kill conjClass=prefix, pattenClass=pattern2, pos=verb
ʔIk(k)In- swallow conjClass=prefix, patternClass=pattern1, pos=verb
ʔInḅIt- step conjClass=prefix, patternClass=pattern1, pos=verb

Morphosyntactic Properties

Arbore paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

pdgmType

  1. exemplary

  2. structure

PNG Properties

  • PNG

    Arbore follows the Cushitic-Omotic PNG Pattern.

  • number

    1. impersonal

    2. pl

    3. sg

  • person

    1. impersonal

    2. p1

    3. p2

    4. p3

Pronoun Properties

  • case

    1. absolutive

    2. nominative

    3. predicative

  • possGen

    1. f

    2. m

  • possNum

    1. pl

    2. sg

  • proClass

    1. boundSubject

    2. deictic

    3. independent

    4. possSuff

    5. possessive

    6. reflEmph

  • proximity

    1. far

    2. near

Verb Selector Properties

  • selProClass

    1. preVerbSel_SubjMarkers

    2. preVerbSelSubjMarkers

  • definite

    1. definite

    2. indefinite

  • mood

    1. indicative

    2. non-indicative

Verb Properties

  • polarity

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • clauseType: There are important formal distinctions between main-clause and relative clause verb forms.

    1. main

    2. relative

  • theme

    1. base

    2. causative1

    3. causative2

    4. inchoative

    5. middle1

    6. middle2

    7. middle3

    8. middle4

    9. passive

  • inflectionClass: as in all languages, phonological and grammaticization processes conspire to create more or less marked morphophonemic differences in the verbal inflections of different sets of verbs.

    • conjClass:

      • prefix

        1. patternClass: two different apophony patterns

          1. irreg1-2

          2. pattern1: i/e

          3. pattern2: e/o ~ a

        2. stemClass

          1. e-stem

          2. i-stem

          3. aa-stem

          4. ee-stem

      • suffix

        1. stemAltClass: category-governed stem alternations (Hayward1984 secc. 5.1.2 and 5.3.2.1; an open set of classes

          1. ad-Class

          2. add-Class

          3. ahad-Class

          4. had-Class

          5. is-Class

          6. m-Class

          7. s-Class

          8. w-Class

        2. subconjClass

          1. contracting: suffix lexical verbs with CVCVC~CVCC alternation

          2. nonContracting: suffix-class lexical verbs without syllabicity alternation

    • morpho-syntactic conditioning

      • subjIdent

        1. ident

        2. nonIdent

      • subjVerbAgr

        1. agreement

        2. nonAgr

    • focus

      1. neutral

      2. non-subj-focus

      3. subj-focus

  • tam

    1. imperfect: "present"

    2. perfect: "past"

    3. pluperfect

    4. general: undifferentiated tense

    5. imperative

    6. jussive

  • special

  • nonFinite

    1. infinitive

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following two tables give the feature-value combinations of the paradigms wich are actually documented in the archive. The first simply lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The second listing gives a spreadsheet-like row-by-column enumeration for the properties which are common to each paradigm; this eventually should be user-sortable to facilitate the comparative study of the paradigms. The second simply lists the common property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

The Western Omo-Tana language, Dhaasanac is spoken in Ethiopia and Kenya in villages along the lower Omo river and near Lake Turkana.

Bibliographic Source

[Tosco2001b] The Dhaasanac language: grammar, texts, vocabulary of a Cushitic language of Ethiopia. Kuschitische Sprachstudien. vol. 17. Köln: Köppe Verlag. 2001. Mauro Tosco.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

General Information

Location-Speakers

The Western Omo-Tana language, Elmolo was spoken in Kenya on the southeastern shore of Lake Turkana; it is not certain whether there are still any speakers .

Bibliographic Source

[Heine1980d] Elmolo. Bernd Heine. 173-219. The Non-Bantu Languages of Kenya. Language and Dialect Atlas of Kenya, vol. 2. Berlin: Dietrich Reimer Verlag. 1980. Bernd Heine.

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

PNG Properties

    1. base

    2. possessive

    3. subject

  • type

    1. independent

    2. possessiveSuffix

Verb Properties

  • polarity

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • theme

    1. base

    2. causative

    3. middle

    4. passive

  • tam

    • simple

      1. present

      2. past

      3. jussive

      4. imperative

    • compound

  • nonFinite

    1. infinitive

  • inflectionClass: as in all languages, phonological and grammaticization processes conspire to create more or less marked morphophonemic differences in the verbal inflections of different sets of verbs.

    • affixationClass:

      • prefixConjugation

        1. sub-class1

        2. sub-class2

        3. etc.

        4. etc.

      • suffixConjugation

        1. sub-class1

        2. sub-class2

        3. etc.

        4. etc.

  • special

number:pl,sg

Chapter 42.  Akkadian-OB Language Data

Table of Contents

General Information
Location-Speakers
Bibliographic Source
akkadian-OB Paradigm Lexemes
Morphosyntactic Properties
Attested Archive Paradigms
Phonological Inventory

General Information

Location-Speakers

Old Babylonian is a variety of the Semitic Akkadian language-group, a closely related set of geographically and chronologically differentiated language varieties attested in written (cuneiform) sources from Mesopotamia (roughly, present-day Iraq) from the middle of the third millennium to the last centuries B.C.E. Old Babylonian as documented here is the standard variety of the language used in Southern Mesopotamia, centered around the political capitol Baylon during the first half of the second millennium B.C.E.

Bibliographic Source

There is a huge scholarly literature on Old Babylonian. The source followed here is the excellent pedagogical grammar:

[Huehnergard1997 ] A Grammar of Akkadian . John Huehnergard. Eisenbrauns. Winona Lake, IN. Copyright © 1997. Harvard Semitic Series .

wšr release lemma=wšr, gloss=release, setfree=pdgmLexLabel, attributes={
šriq steal ablautClass=iClass, rootClass=CCC
šāl ask CāC=rootClass
šʾl ask rootClass=CūC
šʾm buy rootClass=CūC
ḫdu be glad rootClass=CCu
ṣbat seize ablautClass=aClass, rootClass=CCC

Morphosyntactic Properties

OB Akkadian paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

PNG Properties

  • PNG

    OB Akkadian, in common with the rest of Semitic has a more extensive (and more archaic) set of gender distinctions than is found in Cushitic outside of Beja:

    number person gender
    sg p1 "⊤"
    sg p2 "m"
    sg p2 "f"
    sg p3 m
    sg p3 m
    sg p3 f
    pl p1 "⊤"
    pl p2 "m"
    pl p2 "f"
    pl p3 "m"
    pl p3 "f"

    I.e., where gender is distinguished not only in the third-person singular, but also in the third-person plural, and in the second-person singular and plural.

Pronoun Properties

  • case

    1. accusative

    2. dative

    3. genAcc

    4. genitive

    5. nominative

    6. oblique

    7. possessive

  • deixis

    1. far

    2. near

  • genHead

    1. f

    2. m

  • numHead

    1. pl

    2. sg

  • proClass

    1. demonstrative

    2. independent

    3. objClitic

    4. possInd

    5. possessive

Verb Properties

  • polarity

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • theme

    1. B: base stem

    2. Bt: base stem with infixed -t-

    3. Btn: base stem with infixed -tan-

    4. D: geminated (double; "factive") stem

    5. Dt: geminated stem with infixed -t-

    6. Dtn: geminated stem with infixed -tan-

    7. N: N (passive) stem

    8. Ntn N stem with infixed -tan-

    9. S: Š (causative) stem

    10. St: Š stem with infixed -t-

    11. Stn: Š stem with infixed -tan-

    12. Ventive: stem which can be formed from all theme-stems by suffixation of -am (where -m- assimilates to following consonant)and which basically indicates orientation toward speaker (as in {alākum} 'to go' {alākum}+-am 'to come'), but with many other variant semantic effects.

  • inflectionClass: as in all languages, phonological and grammaticization processes conspire to create more or less marked morphophonemic differences in the verbal inflections of different sets of verbs.

    • rootClass

      1. CCC

      2. CCa

      3. CCe

      4. CCi

      5. CCu

      6. CCw

      7. CiC

      8. CuC

      9. CēC

      10. CūC

      11. aCC

      12. alk

      13. eCC

      14. nCC

      15. wCC

    • ablautClass

      2. a-iClass

      3. a-uClass

      4. aClass

      5. e-uClass

      6. eClass

      7. iClass

      8. uClass

      9. ⊤

  • tam

    1. present

    2. preterite

    3. perfect: a tense specific to Akkadian, formed by -t- infixation.

    4. imperative

    5. precative: For first and third person (thus suppletive with the imperative; prefix l(i)- for third person (no gender distinction in the singular!), l(u)- for first person singular, i- for first person plural. Corresponds to the general Semitic jussive.

    6. vetitive: preterite with prefix ayy(_i)~ē-(otherwise)

  • verbMorphClass

    1. dervStem

    2. subjMarker

  • special

  • nonFinite

    1. infinitive

    2. Participle

    3. VerbalAdj

Attested Archive Paradigms

The following two tables give the feature-value combinations of the paradigms wich are actually documented in the archive. The first simply lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The second listing gives a spreadsheet-like row-by-column enumeration for the properties which are common to each paradigm; this eventually should be user-sortable to facilitate the comparative study of the paradigms. The second simply lists the common property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

Hebrew Paradigm Lexemes

The following lexical items are used in the verbal paradigms:

lemma gloss properties

Hebrew Morphosyntactic Properties

Hebrew paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

PNG Properties

  • PNG

    %-link linkend="cushOmPNG"-% Cushitic-Omotic Pattern%-/link-%.

Pronoun Properties

  • case

    1. base

    2. possessive

    3. subject

  • type

    1. independent

    2. possessiveSuffix

Verb Properties

  • polarity

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • theme

    1. base

    2. causative

    3. middle

    4. passive

  • tam

    • simple

      1. present

      2. past

      3. jussive

      4. imperative

    • compound

  • nonFinite

    1. infinitive

  • inflectionClass: as in all languages, phonological and grammaticization processes conspire to create more or less marked morphophonemic differences in the verbal inflections of different sets of verbs.

    • affixationClass:

      • prefixConjugation

        1. sub-class1

        2. sub-class2

        3. etc.

        4. etc.

      • suffixConjugation

        1. sub-class1

        2. sub-class2

        3. etc.

        4. etc.

  • special

Hebrew Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].

paradigmLabel paradigmLex theme clauseType polarity tam inflectionType note

Geez Morphosyntactic Properties

Geez paradigms employ the following property-value dimenstions

PNG Properties

  • PNG

    %-link linkend="cushOmPNG"-% Cushitic-Omotic Pattern%-/link-%.

Pronoun Properties

  • case

    1. base

    2. possessive

    3. subject

  • type

    1. independent

    2. possessiveSuffix

Verb Properties

  • polarity

    1. affirmative

    2. negative

  • theme

    1. base

    2. causative

    3. middle

    4. passive

  • tam

    • simple

      1. present

      2. past

      3. jussive

      4. imperative

    • compound

  • nonFinite

    1. infinitive

  • inflectionClass: as in all languages, phonological and grammaticization processes conspire to create more or less marked morphophonemic differences in the verbal inflections of different sets of verbs.

    • affixationClass:

      • prefixConjugation

        1. sub-class1

        2. sub-class2

        3. etc.

        4. etc.

      • suffixConjugation

        1. sub-class1

        2. sub-class2

        3. etc.

        4. etc.

  • special

Geez Attested Archive Paradigms

The following tabel lists the shared property=value pairs for each paradigm, and then the variable property=value-list (comma separated). The abbreviation "PNG" in the paradigm variable-value lists stnads for:


gender:f,m,⊤
number:pl,sg 
person:p1,p2,p3

I.e., the PNG combinations normal with finite tam-forms.Clicking on the paradigmLabel will yield a display of the paradigm in question [either by link to hard-coded term cluster, or canned SPARQL query].
